# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: moving-parts
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] The **American National Standards Institute** (**ANSI**) is a private nonprofit organization that oversees the development of voluntary consensus standards for products, services, processes, systems, and personnel in the United States.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] The organization also coordinates U.S. standards with international standards so that American products can be used worldwide.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI accredits standards that are developed by representatives of other standards organizations, government agencies, consumer groups, companies, and others.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] These standards ensure that the characteristics and performance of products are consistent, that people use the same definitions and terms, and that products are tested the same way.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI also accredits standards developing organizations (SDOs) and provides a searchable directory of accredited standards developers (ASDs).
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI similarly accredits organizations that carry out product or personnel certification in accordance with requirements defined in international standards.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] The organization's headquarters are in Washington, D.C.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's operations office is located in New York City.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] The ANSI annual operating budget is funded by the sale of publications, membership dues and fees, accreditation services, fee-based programs, and international standards programs.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] Many ANSI regulations are incorporated by reference into United States federal statutes (i.e. by OSHA regulations referring to individual ANSI specifications).
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI does not make these standards publicly available, and charges money for access to these documents; it further claims that it is copyright infringement for them to be provided to the public by others free of charge.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] These assertions have been the subject of criticism and litigation.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI was most likely formed in 1918, when five engineering societies and three government agencies founded the **American Engineering Standards Committee** (**AESC**).
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] In 1928, the AESC became the **American Standards Association** (**ASA**).
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] In 1966, the ASA was reorganized and became the **United States of America Standards Institute** (**USASI**).
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] In February 1969, Ralph Nader harshly criticized the USASI in public remarks as "manifestly deceptive" in several different ways.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] He specifically attacked the name USASI as improperly implying some kind of official connection with the federal government of the United States.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] had been members of the United Engineering Society (UES).
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] At the behest of the AIEE, they invited the U.S. government Departments of War, Navy (combined in 1947 to become the Department of Defense or DOD) and Commerce to join in founding a national standards organization.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] According to Adam Stanton, the first permanent secretary and head of staff in 1919, AESC started as an ambitious program and little else.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] Staff for the first year consisted of one executive, Clifford B.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] LePage, who was on loan from a founding member, ASME.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] An annual budget of $7,500 was provided by the founding bodies.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] In 1931, the organization (renamed ASA in 1928) became affiliated with the U.S.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] National Committee of the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), which had been formed in 1904 to develop electrical and electronics standards.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's members are government agencies, organizations, academic and international bodies, and individuals.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] In total, the Institute represents the interests of more than 270,000 companies and organizations and 30 million professionals worldwide.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's market-driven, decentralized approach has been criticized in comparison with more planned and organized international approaches to standardization.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] Although ANSI itself does not develop standards, the Institute oversees the development and use of standards by accrediting the procedures of standards developing organizations.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI accreditation signifies that the procedures used by standards developing organizations meet the institute's requirements for openness, balance, consensus, and due process.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI also designates specific standards as American National Standards, or ANS, when the Institute determines that the standards were developed in an environment that is equitable, accessible and responsive to the requirements of various stakeholders.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] Voluntary consensus standards quicken the market acceptance of products while making clear how to improve the safety of those products for the protection of consumers.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] There are approximately 9,500 American National Standards that carry the ANSI designation.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] The institute is the official U.S. representative to the two major international standards organizations, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), as a founding member, and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), via the U.S.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI participates in almost the entire technical program of both the ISO and the IEC, and administers many key committees and subgroups.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] In many instances, U.S. standards are taken forward to ISO and IEC, through ANSI or the USNC, where they are adopted in whole or in part as international standards.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] Adoption of ISO and IEC standards as American standards increased from 0.2% in 1986 to 15.5% in May 2012.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] Each of the panels works to identify, coordinate, and harmonize voluntary standards relevant to these areas.
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] In 2009, ANSI and the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) formed the Nuclear Energy Standards Coordination Collaborative (NESCC).
[src:moving-parts/american-national-standards-institute] NESCC is a joint initiative to identify and respond to the current need for standards in the nuclear industry.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Founded as an engineering society focused on mechanical engineering in North America, ASME is today multidisciplinary and global.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has over 85,000 members in more than 135 countries worldwide.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME was founded in 1880 in response to numerous steam boiler pressure vessel failures by Alexander Lyman Holley, Henry Rossiter Worthington, John Edison Sweet and Matthias N.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Forney, with Robert Henry Thurston as the society's founding president.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Known for setting codes and standards for mechanical devices, ASME conducts one of the world's largest technical publishing operations.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] It holds numerous technical conferences and hundreds of professional development courses each year and sponsors numerous outreach and educational programs.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Ned Djilali and Georgia Tech president and woman engineer supporter Blake R Van Leer were executive members.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Kate Gleason and Lydia Weld were the first two women members.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME is one of the oldest standards-developing organizations in America.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] It produces approximately 600 codes and standards covering many technical areas, such as fasteners, plumbing fixtures, elevators, pipelines, and power plant systems and components.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME's standards are developed by committees of subject matter experts using an open, consensus-based process.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Many ASME standards are cited by government agencies as tools to meet their regulatory objectives.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME standards are therefore voluntary, unless the standards have been incorporated into a legally binding business contract or incorporated into regulations enforced by an authority having jurisdiction, such as a federal, state, or local government agency.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME's standards are used in more than 100 countries and have been translated into numerous languages.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The largest ASME standard, both in size and in the number of volunteers involved in its preparation, is the ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code (BPVC).
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The BPVC provides rules for the design, fabrication, installation, inspection, care, and use of boilers, pressure vessels, and nuclear components.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The code also includes standards on materials, welding and brazing procedures and qualifications, nondestructive examination, and nuclear in-service inspection.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In addition to academic journals, since 1880 the ASME has also published the magazine *Mechanical Engineering*.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] This means the nominees need not be professional educators.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] (1879–1964), an ASME Member and professor of mechanical engineering and head of the department at the Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn, established the Medal.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME runs several annual E-Fests, or Engineering Festivals, taking the place of the Student Professional Development Conference (SPDC) series.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In addition to the Human Powered Vehicle Challenge (HPVC), the Innovative Additive Manufacturing 3D Challenge (IAM3D), the Student Design Competition, and the Old Guard Competition, there are also talks, interactive workshops, and entertainment.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] These events allows students to network with working engineers, host contests, and promote ASME's benefits to students as well as professionals.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] E-Fests are held in four regions in the United States and internationally—western U.S, eastern U.S., Asia Pacific, and South America—with the E-Fest location for each region changing every year.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME holds a variety of competitions every year for engineering students from around the world.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has four key offices in the United States, including its headquarters operation in New York, N.Y., and three international offices in Beijing, China; Brussels, Belgium, and New Delhi, India.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has two institutes and 32 technical divisions within its organizational structure.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In 1982, ASME was found to be the first non-profit organization to in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:moving-parts/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The United States Supreme Court found the organization liable for more than $6 million in *American Society of Mechanical Engineers v.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] The direction ${\hat {\boldsymbol {\omega }}}={\boldsymbol {\omega }}/\|{\boldsymbol {\omega }}\|$ is normal to the instantaneous plane of rotation.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] The sense of angular velocity is conventionally specified by the right-hand rule, implying clockwise rotations (as viewed on the plane of rotation); negation (multiplication by −1) leaves the magnitude unchanged but flips the axis in the opposite direction.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] The magnitude of this vector, $\omega =\|{\boldsymbol {\omega }}\|$ , represents the *angular speed*, the angular rate at which the object rotates (spins or revolves).
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] The angular velocity as given above for point particles, is called orbital angular velocity.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] A rigid body rotating about a fixed axis has each point of the body having the same orbital angular velocity.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] Hence such a rigid body can be given an angular velocity (called spin angular velocity) equal to the orbital angular velocity of each point in the body.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] The angular velocity, as given above for rotation in a fixed circle at constant speed, can be generalized to more general motion in three dimensions.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] Angular velocity has dimension of per unit time.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] The SI unit of angular velocity is radians per second,.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] The radian is a dimensionless quantity, thus the SI units of angular velocity are dimensionally equivalent to reciprocal seconds, s−1, although rad/s is preferable to avoid confusion with **rotational velocity** in units of hertz (also equivalent to s−1).
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] If angle is measured in radians, the linear velocity is the radius times the angular velocity, ⁠ $v=r\omega$ ⁠.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] With orbital radius 42000 km from the Earth's center, the satellite's tangential speed through space is thus *v* = 42000 km × 0.26/h ≈ 11000 km/h.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] The angular velocity is positive since the satellite travels prograde with the Earth's rotation (the same direction as the rotation of Earth).
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] In the simplest case of circular motion at radius ⁠ r ⁠, with position given by the angular displacement $\phi (t)$ from the x-axis, the orbital angular velocity is the rate of change of angle with respect to time: ⁠ $\textstyle \omega ={\frac {d\phi }{dt}}$ ⁠.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] If $\phi$ is measured in radians, the arc-length from the positive x-axis around the circle to the particle is ⁠ $\ell =r\phi$ ⁠, and the linear velocity is ⁠ $\textstyle v(t)={\frac {d\ell }{dt}}=r\omega (t)$ ⁠, so that ⁠ $\textstyle \omega ={\frac {v}{r}}$ ⁠.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] In the general case of a particle moving in the plane, the orbital angular velocity is the rate at which the position vector relative to a chosen origin "sweeps out" angle.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] The diagram shows the position vector $\mathbf {r}$ from the origin O to a particle ⁠ P ⁠, with its polar coordinates ⁠ $(r,\phi )$ ⁠.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] When there is no radial component, the particle moves around the origin in a circle; but when there is no cross-radial component, it moves in a straight line from the origin.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] Since radial motion leaves the angle unchanged, only the cross-radial component of linear velocity contributes to angular velocity.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] Here the cross-radial speed $v_{\perp }$ is the signed magnitude of ⁠ $\mathbf {v} _{\perp }$ ⁠, positive for counter-clockwise motion, negative for clockwise.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] These formulas may be derived doing ⁠ $\mathbf {r} =(r\cos(\varphi ),r\sin(\varphi ))$ ⁠, being r a function of the distance to the origin with respect to time, and $\varphi$ a function of the angle between the vector and the x-axis.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] In two dimensions, angular velocity is a number with plus or minus sign indicating orientation, but not pointing in a direction.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] The sign is conventionally taken to be positive if the radius vector turns counter-clockwise, and negative if clockwise.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] Angular velocity then may be termed a pseudoscalar, a numerical quantity which changes sign under a parity inversion, such as inverting one axis or switching the two axes.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] In three-dimensional space, we again have the position vector **r** of a moving particle.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] Here, orbital angular velocity is a pseudovector whose magnitude is the rate at which **r** sweeps out angle (in radians per unit of time), and whose direction is perpendicular to the instantaneous plane in which **r** sweeps out angle (i.e. the plane spanned by **r** and **v**).
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] However, as there are *two* directions perpendicular to any plane, an additional condition is necessary to uniquely specify the direction of the angular velocity; conventionally, the right-hand rule is used.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] Let the pseudovector $\mathbf {u}$ be the unit vector perpendicular to the plane spanned by **r** and **v**, so that the right-hand rule is satisfied (i.e. the instantaneous direction of angular displacement is counter-clockwise looking from the top of ⁠ $\mathbf {u}$ ⁠).
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] where ⁠ $\theta$ ⁠ is the angle between ⁠ $\mathbf {r}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {v}$ ⁠.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] Given a rotating frame of three linearly independent unit coordinate vectors, at each instant in time, there always exists a common axis (called the axis of rotation) around which all three vectors rotate with the same angular speed and in the same angular direction (clockwise or counterclockwise).
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] In such a frame, each vector may be considered as a moving particle with constant scalar radius.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] A collection of such particles is called a rigid body.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] In larger than 3 spatial dimensions, the interpretation of spin angular velocity as a pseudovector is not valid; however, it may be characterized by a more general type of object known as an antisymmetric rank-2 tensor.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] The addition of angular velocity vectors for frames is also defined by the usual vector addition (composition of linear movements), and can be useful to decompose the rotation as in a gimbal.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] All components of the vector can be calculated as derivatives of the parameters defining the moving frames (Euler angles or rotation matrices).
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] Consider a rigid body rotating about a fixed point O.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] Construct a reference frame in the body consisting of an orthonormal set of vectors $\mathbf {e} _{1},\mathbf {e} _{2},\mathbf {e} _{3}$ fixed to the body and with their common origin at O.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] where ${\dot {\mathbf {e} }}_{i}={\frac {d\mathbf {e} _{i}}{dt}}$ is the time rate of change of the frame vector ⁠ $\mathbf {e} _{i},i=1,2,3$ ⁠, due to the rotation.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] as that formula defines angular velocity for a *single point* about O, while the formula in this section applies to a frame or rigid body.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] In the case of a rigid body a *single* ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}$ has to account for the motion of *all* particles in the body.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] Euler proved that the projections of the angular velocity pseudovector on each of these three axes is the derivative of its associated angle (which is equivalent to decomposing the instantaneous rotation into three instantaneous Euler rotations).
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] This basis is not orthonormal and it is difficult to use, but now the velocity vector can be changed to the fixed frame or to the moving frame with just a change of bases.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] where ${\hat {\mathbf {i} }},{\hat {\mathbf {j} }},{\hat {\mathbf {k} }}$ are unit vectors for the frame fixed in the moving body.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] This example has been made using the Z-X-Z convention for Euler angles.
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] The scalar elements above correspond to the angular velocity vector components ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}=(\omega _{x},\omega _{y},\omega _{z})$ .
[src:moving-parts/angular-velocity] This is an *infinitesimal rotation matrix*.
