[src:moving-parts/animation] Animation is contrasted with live action, although the two do not exist in isolation.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Many filmmakers have produced films that are a hybrid of the two.
[src:moving-parts/animation] As CGI increasingly approximates photographic imagery, filmmakers can relatively easily composite 3D animated visual effects (VFX) into their film, rather than using practical effects.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Computer animation can be very detailed 3D animation, while 2D computer animation (which may have the look of traditional animation) can be used for stylistic reasons, low bandwidth, or faster real-time renderings.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Other common animation methods apply a stop motion technique to two- and three-dimensional objects like paper cutouts, puppets, or clay figures.
[src:moving-parts/animation] An **animated cartoon**, or simply a **cartoon**, is an animated film, usually a short film, that features an exaggerated style.
[src:moving-parts/animation] This style is often inspired by comic strips, gag cartoons, and other non-animated art forms.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Cartoons frequently include anthropomorphic animals, superheroes, or the adventures of human protagonists.
[src:moving-parts/animation] The action often revolves around exaggerated physical humor, particularly in predator and prey dynamics (e.g. cats and mice, coyotes and birds), where violent pratfalls such as falls, collisions, and explosions occur, often in ways that would be lethal in the real life.
[src:moving-parts/animation] During the late 1980s, the term "cartoon" was shortened to ***toon***, referring to characters in animated productions, or more specifically, cartoonishly-drawn characters.
[src:moving-parts/animation] This term gained popularity first in 1988 with the live-action/animated hybrid film *Who Framed Roger Rabbit*, which introduced ToonTown, a world inhabited by various animated cartoon characters.
[src:moving-parts/animation] In 1990, *Tiny Toon Adventures* embraced the classic cartoon spirit, introducing a new generation of cartoon characters.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Then, in 1993, *Animaniacs* followed, featuring the three rubber-hose-styled Warner siblings, Yakko, Wakko, and Dot, who are trapped in the 1930s, eventually escaped and found themselves in the Warner Bros. water tower in the 1990s.
[src:moving-parts/animation] The illusion of animation—as in motion pictures in general—has traditionally been attributed to the persistence of vision and later to the phi phenomenon and beta movement, but the exact neurological causes are still uncertain.
[src:moving-parts/animation] The illusion of motion caused by a rapid succession of images that minimally differ from each other, with unnoticeable interruptions, is a stroboscopic effect.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Analog mechanical animation media that rely on the rapid display of sequential images include the phenakistiscope, zoetrope, flip book, praxinoscope, and film.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Television and video are popular electronic animation media that originally were analog and now operate digitally.
[src:moving-parts/animation] For display on computers, technology such as the animated GIF and Flash animation were developed.
[src:moving-parts/animation] In addition to short films, feature films, television series, animated GIFs, and other media dedicated to the display of moving images, animation is also prevalent in video games, motion graphics, user interfaces, and visual effects.
[src:moving-parts/animation] The physical movement of image parts through simple mechanics—for instance, moving images in magic lantern shows—can also be considered animation.
[src:moving-parts/animation] The mechanical manipulation of three-dimensional puppets and objects to emulate living beings has a very long history in automata.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Electronic automata were popularized by Disney as animatronics.
[src:moving-parts/animation] The word *animation* comes from the Latin word *animātiō*, meaning 'bestowing of life'.
[src:moving-parts/animation] The earlier meaning of the English word is 'liveliness' and has been in use much longer than the meaning of 'moving image medium'.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Long before modern animation began, audiences around the world were captivated by the magic of moving characters.
[src:moving-parts/animation] For centuries, master artists and craftsmen have brought puppets, automatons, shadow puppets, and fantastical lanterns to life, inspiring the imagination through physically manipulated wonders.
[src:moving-parts/animation] In 1832, the phenakistoscope, invented by Belgian Joseph Plateau, would introduce the principle of modern animation, the principle of persistence of vision.
[src:moving-parts/animation] The principle would be later applied by William George Horner's zoetrope (1876), the flip book (1868), the praxinoscope(1877), and film.
[src:moving-parts/animation] The device was operated by spinning the cardboard disc and viewing the reflection of the image in a mirror through a series of moving slits, which created the illusion that the image was moving.Similarly, the zoetrope was operated by spinning a rotating drum lined up with a strip of pictures inside.
[src:moving-parts/animation] In 1876, animation would be adapted for the theatrical audience, as entrepreneurs such as Emile Reynaud began investing in the art form.
[src:moving-parts/animation] It wasn't until the invention of sprocket-drive film stock, would animation begin to gain traction in cinema.
[src:moving-parts/animation] When cinematography eventually broke through in the 1890s, the wonder of the realistic details in the new medium was seen as its biggest accomplishment.
[src:moving-parts/animation] It took years before animation found its way to the cinemas.
[src:moving-parts/animation] The successful short *The Haunted Hotel* (1907) by J.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Stuart Blackton popularized stop motion and reportedly inspired Émile Cohl to create *Fantasmagorie* (1908), regarded as the oldest known example of a complete traditional (hand-drawn) animation on standard cinematographic film.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Other great artistic and very influential short films were created by Ladislas Starevich with his puppet animations since 1910 and by Winsor McCay with detailed hand-drawn animation in films such as *Little Nemo* (1911) and *Gertie the Dinosaur* (1914).
[src:moving-parts/animation] During the 1910s, the production of animated "cartoons" became an industry in the US.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Successful producer John Randolph Bray and animator Earl Hurd patented the cel animation process that dominated the animation industry for the rest of the century.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Felix the Cat, who debuted in 1919, became the first fully realized anthropomorphic animal character in the history of American animation.
[src:moving-parts/animation] The characteristics of Felix the cat's physical appearance would come to be the standard model for cartoon character in the following years.
[src:moving-parts/animation] In 1928, *Steamboat Willie*, featuring Mickey Mouse and Minnie Mouse, popularized film-with-synchronized-sound and put Walt Disney's studio at the forefront of the animation industry.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Although Disney Animation's actual output relative to total global animation output has always been very small, the studio has overwhelmingly dominated the "aesthetic norms" of animation ever since.
[src:moving-parts/animation] The enormous success of Mickey Mouse is seen as the start of the golden age of American animation that would last until the 1960s.
[src:moving-parts/animation] The United States dominated the world market of animation with a plethora of cel-animated theatrical shorts.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Coyote and the Road Runner (1949), MGM cartoon studio's Tom and Jerry (1940) and Droopy, Universal Cartoon Studios' Woody Woodpecker (1940), Terrytoons/20th Century Fox's Mighty Mouse (1942), and United Artists' Pink Panther (1963).
[src:moving-parts/animation] After working on it for three years, Lotte Reiniger released the German feature-length silhouette animation *Die Abenteuer des Prinzen Achmed* in 1926, the oldest extant animated feature.
[src:moving-parts/animation] In 1917, Italian-Argentine director Quirino Cristiani made the first feature-length film *El Apóstol* (now lost), which became a critical and commercial success.
[src:moving-parts/animation] It was followed by Cristiani's *Sin dejar rastros* in 1918, but one day after its premiere, the film was confiscated by the government.
[src:moving-parts/animation] In 1937, Walt Disney Studios premiered their first animated feature *Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs*, still one of the highest-grossing traditional animation features as of May 2020.
[src:moving-parts/animation] The Fleischer studios followed this example in 1939 with *Gulliver's Travels* with some success.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Partly due to foreign markets being cut off by the Second World War, Disney's next features *Pinocchio*, *Fantasia* (both 1940), Fleischer Studios' second animated feature *Mr.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Bug Goes to Town* (1941–1942) failed at the box office.
[src:moving-parts/animation] For several decades, Disney was the only American studio to regularly produce animated features, until Ralph Bakshi became the first to release more than a handful of features.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Sullivan-Bluth Studios began to regularly produce animated features starting with *An American Tail* in 1986.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Although relatively few titles became as successful as Disney's features, other countries developed their own animation industries that produced both short and feature theatrical animations in a wide variety of styles, relatively often including stop motion and cutout animation techniques.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Soviet Soyuzmultfilm animation studio, founded in 1936, produced 20 films (including shorts) per year on average and reached 1,582 titles in 2018.
[src:moving-parts/animation] China, Czechoslovakia / Czech Republic, Italy, France, and Belgium were other countries that more than occasionally released feature films.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Animation became very popular on television since the 1950s, when television sets started to become common in most developed countries.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Cartoons were mainly programmed for children, on convenient time slots, and especially US youth spent many hours watching Saturday-morning cartoons.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Many classic cartoons found a new life on the small screen and by the end of the 1950s, the production of new animated cartoons started to shift from theatrical releases to TV series.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Hanna-Barbera Productions was especially prolific and had huge hit series, such as *The Flintstones* (1960–1966) (the first prime time animated series), *Scooby-Doo* (since 1969) and Belgian co-production *The Smurfs* (1981–1989).
[src:moving-parts/animation] The constraints of American television programming and the demand for an enormous quantity resulted in cheaper and quicker limited animation methods and much more formulaic scripts.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Quality dwindled until more daring animation surfaced in the late 1980s and in the early 1990s with hit series, the first cartoon of The Simpsons (1987), which later developed into its own show (in 1989) and *SpongeBob SquarePants* (since 1999) as part of a "renaissance" of American animation.
[src:moving-parts/animation] While US animated series also spawned successes internationally, many other countries produced their own child-oriented programming, relatively often preferring stop motion and puppetry over cel animation.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Computer animation was gradually developed since the 1940s.
[src:moving-parts/animation] 3D wireframe animation started popping up in the mainstream in the 1970s, with an early (short) appearance in the sci-fi thriller *Futureworld* (1976).
[src:moving-parts/animation] The so-called 3D style, more often associated with computer animation, became the dominant technique following the success of Pixar's *Toy Story* (1995), the first computer-animated feature in this style.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Most of the cel animation studios switched to producing mostly computer-animated films around the 1990s, as it proved cheaper and more profitable.
[src:moving-parts/animation] In 2010, the animation market was estimated to be worth circa US$80 billion.
[src:moving-parts/animation] By 2021, the value had increased to an estimated US$370 billion.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Animated feature-length films returned the highest gross margins (around 52%) of all film genres between 2004 and 2013.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Animation as an art and industry continues to thrive as of the early 2020s.
[src:moving-parts/animation] The clarity of animation makes it a powerful tool for instruction, while its total malleability also allows exaggeration that can be employed to convey strong emotions and to thwart reality.
[src:moving-parts/animation] It has therefore been widely used for other purposes than mere entertainment.
[src:moving-parts/animation] During World War II, animation was widely exploited for propaganda.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Many American studios, including Warner Bros. and Disney, lent their talents and their cartoon characters to convey to the public certain war values.
[src:moving-parts/animation] These efforts extended to other countries well into the Cold War era, particularly as it pertained to "combatting" communism.
[src:moving-parts/animation] For example, the English 1954 adaptation of George Orwell's *Animal Farm* (the nation's first feature-length animated film) is speculated to have had its production funded by the CIA.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Animation has been very popular in television commercials, both due to its graphic appeal, and the humour it can provide.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Some animated characters in commercials have survived for decades, such as Snap, Crackle and Pop in advertisements for Kellogg's cereals.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Tex Avery was the producer of the first Raid "Kills Bugs Dead" commercials in 1966, which were very successful for the company.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Apart from their success in movie theatres and television series, many cartoon characters would also prove lucrative when licensed for all kinds of merchandise and for other media.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Animation has traditionally been very closely related to comic books.
[src:moving-parts/animation] While many comic book characters found their way to the screen (which is often the case in Japan, where many manga are adapted into anime), original animated characters also commonly appear in comic books and magazines.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Somewhat similarly, characters and plots for video games (an interactive form of animation that became its own medium) have been derived from films and vice versa.
[src:moving-parts/animation] While very many animation companies commercially exploit their creations outside moving image media, The Walt Disney Company is the best known and most extreme example.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Since first being licensed for a children's writing tablet in 1929, their Mickey Mouse mascot has been depicted on an enormous amount of products, as have many other Disney characters.
[src:moving-parts/animation] This may have influenced some pejorative use of Mickey's name, but licensed Disney products sell well, and the so-called Disneyana has many avid collectors, and even a dedicated Disneyana Fan Club (since 1984).
[src:moving-parts/animation] Disneyland opened in 1955 and features many attractions that were based on Disney's cartoon characters.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Its enormous success spawned several other Disney theme parks and resorts.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Disney's earnings from the theme parks have relatively often been higher than those from their movies.
[src:moving-parts/animation] As with any other form of media, animation has instituted awards for excellence in the field.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Many are part of general or regional film award programs, like the China's Golden Rooster Award for Best Animation (since 1981).
[src:moving-parts/animation] Awards programs dedicated to animation, with many categories, include ASIFA-Hollywood's Annie Awards, the Emile Awards in Europe and the Anima Mundi awards in Brazil.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Apart from Academy Awards for Best Animated Short Film (since 1932) and Best Animated Feature (since 2002), animated movies have been nominated and rewarded in other categories, relatively often for Best Original Song and Best Original Score.
[src:moving-parts/animation] The creation of non-trivial animation works (i.e., longer than a few seconds) has developed as a form of filmmaking, with certain unique aspects.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Traits common to both live-action and animated feature films are labour intensity and high production costs.
[src:moving-parts/animation] The most important difference is that once a film is in the production phase, the marginal cost of one more shot is higher for animated films than live-action films.
[src:moving-parts/animation] It is pointless for a studio to pay the salaries of dozens of animators to spend weeks creating a visually dazzling five-minute scene if that scene fails to effectively advance the plot of the film.
[src:moving-parts/animation] While live-action films are now also storyboarded, they enjoy more latitude to depart from storyboards (i.e., real-time improvisation).
[src:moving-parts/animation] Another problem unique to animation is the requirement to maintain a film's consistency from start to finish, even as films have grown longer and teams have grown larger.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Animators, like all artists, necessarily have individual styles, but must subordinate their individuality in a consistent way to whatever style is employed on a particular film.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Since the early 1980s, teams of about 500 to 600 people, of whom 50 to 70 are animators, typically have created feature-length animated films.
[src:moving-parts/animation] It is relatively easy for two or three artists to match their styles; synchronizing those of dozens of artists is more difficult.
[src:moving-parts/animation] This problem is usually solved by having a separate group of visual development artists develop an overall look and palette for each film before the animation begins.
[src:moving-parts/animation] While animators must "sacrifice their personal drawing styles so that the work of many hands appears to be that of one", visual development artists are allowed to "create new worlds, new characters, and new entertainment possibilities in their own individualistic graphic styles".
[src:moving-parts/animation] Character designers on the visual development team draw model sheets to show how each character should look with different facial expressions, posed in different positions, and viewed from different angles.
[src:moving-parts/animation] On traditionally animated projects, maquettes were often sculpted to further help the animators see how characters would look from different angles.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Unlike live-action films, animated films were traditionally developed beyond the synopsis stage through the storyboard format; the storyboard artists would then receive credit for writing the film.
[src:moving-parts/animation] The traditional approach worked for several decades because prior to the 1960s, no one except Disney was attempting to regularly produce feature-length animated films.
[src:moving-parts/animation] All other animation studios, with occasional exceptions, were producing short films only a few minutes in length.
[src:moving-parts/animation] For short films, it was enough for the storyboard artists to work up a few visual gags and then string them together to form a crude plot.
[src:moving-parts/animation] In 1960, Hanna-Barbera pioneered the longer animated sitcom format for television with *The Flintstones*.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Hanna-Barbera and the other early television animation studios soon discovered that storyboarding was far too inefficient to fill up a half-hour episode on the extremely tight budgets typical of television.
[src:moving-parts/animation] During the 1960s, these studios experimented with a more efficient method for developing story material: a screenwriter is hired to draft a written screenplay which is approved and handed over to the storyboard artists for storyboarding.
[src:moving-parts/animation] This method creates significant tension between screenwriters and storyboard artists, in that some artists feel that people who cannot draw should not be writing for animation, while some writers feel that artists do not understand how to write.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Despite that tension, it has become and remains the dominant method by which animation studios develop both feature-length films and television shows.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Ironically, the Disney studio was relatively slow to adopt this method.
[src:moving-parts/animation] The first Disney feature animated film to have a complete screenplay written and approved before storyboarding was *One Hundred and One Dalmatians* (1961).
[src:moving-parts/animation] However, *101 Dalmatians* was "a short-lived experiment"; the next Disney film to follow this method was *The Great Mouse Detective* (1986).
[src:moving-parts/animation] Finally, another key difference is that actors traditionally record vocal tracks for animated films in separate individual sessions; they often meet one another for the first time only at the film's premiere.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Actors usually schedule sessions in the recording studio around their live-action work.
[src:moving-parts/animation] The traditional cel animation process became obsolete by the beginning of the 21st century.
[src:moving-parts/animation] In modern traditionally animated films, animators' drawings and the backgrounds are either scanned into or drawn directly into a computer system.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Various software programs are used to colour the drawings and simulate camera movement and effects.
[src:moving-parts/animation] The final animated piece is output to one of several delivery media, including traditional 35 mm film and newer media with digital video.
[src:moving-parts/animation] The "look" of traditional cel animation is still preserved, and the character animators' work has remained essentially the same over the past 90 years.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Some animation producers have used the term "tradigital" (a play on the words "traditional" and "digital") to describe cel animation that uses significant computer technology.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Examples of traditionally animated feature films include *Pinocchio* (United States, 1940), *Animal Farm* (United Kingdom, 1954), *Lucky and Zorba* (Italy, 1998), and *The Illusionist* (British-French, 2010).
[src:moving-parts/animation] Stop motion is used to describe animation created by physically manipulating real-world objects and photographing them one frame of film at a time to create the illusion of movement.
[src:moving-parts/animation] There are many different types of stop-motion animation, usually named after the materials used to create the animation.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Computer software is widely available to create this type of animation; traditional stop-motion animation is usually less expensive but more time-consuming to produce than current computer animation.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Typically involves stop-motion puppet figures interacting in a constructed environment, in contrast to real-world interaction in model animation.
[src:moving-parts/animation] inside of them to keep them still and steady to constrain their motion to particular joints.
[src:moving-parts/animation] are puppet-animated films that typically use a different version of a puppet for different frames, rather than manipulating one existing puppet.
[src:moving-parts/animation] It uses figures made of clay or a similar malleable material to create stop-motion animation.
[src:moving-parts/animation] or wire frame inside, similar to the related puppet animation (below), that can be manipulated to pose the figures.
[src:moving-parts/animation] , where clay creatures morph into a variety of different shapes.
[src:moving-parts/animation] (Sometimes called paper animation) A type of stop-motion animation produced by moving two-dimensional pieces of material paper or cloth.
[src:moving-parts/animation] (US, 1997) and the music video Live for the moment, from Verona Riots band (produced by Alberto Serrano and Nívola Uyá, Spain 2014).
[src:moving-parts/animation] A variant of cutout animation in which the characters are backlit and only visible as silhouettes.
[src:moving-parts/animation] by doing cutting, folding, gluing and assembling.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Stop-motion animation created to interact with and exist as a part of a live-action world.
[src:moving-parts/animation] effects and split screens are often employed to blend stop-motion characters or objects with live actors and settings.
[src:moving-parts/animation] between frames of film, which is not present in traditional stop motion.
[src:moving-parts/animation] The use of regular inanimate objects in stop-motion animation, as opposed to specially created items.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Uses non-drawn flat visual graphic material (photographs, newspaper clippings, magazines, etc.), which are sometimes manipulated frame by frame to create movement.
[src:moving-parts/animation] At other times, the graphics remain stationary, while the stop-motion camera is moved to create on-screen action.
[src:moving-parts/animation] or other similar brick toys to make an animation.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Involves the use of live humans as stop-motion characters.
[src:moving-parts/animation] This allows for a number of surreal effects, including disappearances and reappearances, allowing people to appear to slide across the ground, and other effects.
[src:moving-parts/animation] 2D animation figures are created or edited on the computer using 2D bitmap graphics and 2D vector graphics.
[src:moving-parts/animation] This includes automated computerized versions of traditional animation techniques, interpolated morphing, onion skinning and interpolated rotoscoping.
[src:moving-parts/animation] 2D animation has many applications, including After Effects Animation, analog computer animation, Flash animation, and PowerPoint animation.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Cinemagraphs are still photographs in the form of an animated GIF file of which part is animated.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Final line advection animation is a technique used in 2D animation, to give artists and animators more influence and control over the final product as everything is done within the same department.
[src:moving-parts/animation] When working with game animations, skeletal 2D animations are commonly created using tools like Spine, DragonBones, Blender COA Tools, Rive, and the built-in Unity editor.
[src:moving-parts/animation] The primary benefit of this approach is the ability to reuse images, which reduces the amount of graphics stored in RAM.
[src:moving-parts/animation] This principle of maximizing resource efficiency means that by reusing existing elements, you can enhance the visual appeal of animations without needing to create additional graphics.
[src:moving-parts/animation] 3D animation is digitally modelled and manipulated by an animator.
[src:moving-parts/animation] The 3D model maker usually starts by creating a 3D polygon mesh for the animator to manipulate.
[src:moving-parts/animation] A mesh typically includes many vertices that are connected by edges and faces, which give the visual appearance of form to a 3D object or 3D environment.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Sometimes, the mesh is given an internal digital skeletal structure called an armature that can be used to control the mesh by weighting the vertices.
[src:moving-parts/animation] This process is called rigging and can be used in conjunction with key frames to create movement.
[src:moving-parts/animation] Other techniques can be applied, mathematical functions (e.g., gravity, particle simulations), simulated fur or hair, and effects, fire and water simulations.
[src:moving-parts/animation] These techniques fall under the category of 3D dynamics.
[src:moving-parts/annual-review-of-materials-science] The ***Annual Review of Materials Research*** is a peer-reviewed journal that publishes review articles about materials science.
[src:moving-parts/annual-review-of-materials-science] It has been published by the nonprofit Annual Reviews since 1971, when it was first released under the title the ***Annual Review of Materials Science***.
[src:moving-parts/annual-review-of-materials-science] Four people have served as editors, with the current editor Ram Seshadri stepping into the position in 2024.
[src:moving-parts/annual-review-of-materials-science] As of 2023, it is being published as open access, under the Subscribe to Open model.
[src:moving-parts/annual-review-of-materials-science] As of 2025, *Journal Citation Reports* gives the journal a 2024 impact factor of 10.4.
[src:moving-parts/annual-review-of-materials-science] The *Annual Review of Materials Science* was first published in 1971 by the nonprofit publisher Annual Reviews, making it their sixteenth journal.
[src:moving-parts/annual-review-of-materials-science] In 2001, its name was changed to the current form, the *Annual Review of Materials Research*.
[src:moving-parts/annual-review-of-materials-science] The name change was intended "to better reflect the broad appeal that materials research has for so many diverse groups of scientists and not simply those who identify themselves with the academic discipline of materials science." As of 2020, it was published both in print and electronically.
[src:moving-parts/annual-review-of-materials-science] It defines its scope as covering significant developments in the field of materials science, including methodologies for studying materials and materials phenomena.
[src:moving-parts/annual-review-of-materials-science] As of 2025, *Journal Citation Reports* gives the journal a 2024 impact factor of 10.4 ranking it fifty-seventh of 460 titles in the category "Materials Science, Multidisciplinary".
[src:moving-parts/annual-review-of-materials-science] It is abstracted and indexed in Scopus, Science Citation Index Expanded, Civil Engineering Abstracts, INSPEC, and Academic Search, among others.
[src:moving-parts/annual-review-of-materials-science] The *Annual Review of Materials Research* is helmed by the editor or the co-editors.
[src:moving-parts/annual-review-of-materials-science] The editor is assisted by the editorial committee, which includes associate editors, regular members, and occasionally guest editors.
[src:moving-parts/annual-review-of-materials-science] Guest members participate at the invitation of the editor, and serve terms of one year.
[src:moving-parts/annual-review-of-materials-science] All other members of the editorial committee are appointed by the Annual Reviews board of directors and serve five-year terms.
[src:moving-parts/annual-review-of-materials-science] The editorial committee determines which topics should be included in each volume and solicits reviews from qualified authors.
[src:moving-parts/annual-review-of-materials-science] Unsolicited manuscripts are not accepted.
[src:moving-parts/annual-review-of-materials-science] Peer review of accepted manuscripts is undertaken by the editorial committee.
[src:moving-parts/annual-review-of-materials-science] Dates indicate publication years in which someone was credited as a lead editor or co-editor of a journal volume.
[src:moving-parts/annual-review-of-materials-science] The planning process for a volume begins well before the volume appears, so appointment to the position of lead editor generally occurred prior to the first year shown here.
[src:moving-parts/annual-review-of-materials-science] An editor who has retired or died may be credited as a lead editor of a volume that they helped to plan, even if it is published after their retirement or death.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] There are a variety of propulsion systems available or potentially available for automobiles and other vehicles.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] Options included internal combustion engines (ICE) fueled by petrol, diesel, propane, or natural gas; hybrid vehicles, plug-in hybrids, fuel cell vehicles fueled by hydrogen and all electric cars.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] Fueled vehicles seem to have the advantage due to the limited range and high cost of batteries.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] Some options required construction of a network of fueling or charging stations.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] With no compelling advantage for any particular option, car makers pursued parallel development tracks using a variety of options.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] Reducing the weight of vehicles was one strategy being employed.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] The chief characteristic of an automotive engine (compared to a stationary engine or a marine engine) is a high power-to-weight ratio.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] This is achieved by using a high rotational speed.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] However, automotive engines are sometimes modified for marine use, forming a marine automobile engine.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] In the early years, steam engines and electric motors were tried, but with limited success.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] In the 20th century, the internal combustion engine (ICE), became dominant.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] In 2015, the internal combustion engine remains the most widely used but a resurgence of electricity seems likely because of increasing concern about ICE engine exhaust gas emissions.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] As of 2017, the majority of the cars in the United States are gasoline powered.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] In the early 1900s, the internal combustion engines faced competition from steam engines and electric motors.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] The internal combustion engines of the time were powered by gasoline.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] Internal combustion engines function with the concept of a piston being pushed by the pressure of a certain explosion.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] This explosion is burning the hydrocarbon within the cylinder of an engine.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] Out of all the cars manufactured during the time, only around one fourth are actually considered internal combustion.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] Within the next couple of years, the internal combustion engine came out to become the most popular automotive engine.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] Sometime within the 19th century, Rudolf Diesel invented a new form of internal combustion power, using a concept of injecting liquid fuel into air heated solely by compression.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] This is the predecessor to the modern diesel engine used in automobiles, but more specifically, heavy duty vehicles such as semi-trucks.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] Petrol engines quickly became the choice of manufacturers and consumers alike.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] Despite the rough start, noisy and dirty engine, and the difficult gear shifting, new technologies such as the production line and the advancement of the engine allowed the standard production of the gas automobiles.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] This is the start, from the invention of the gas automobile in 1876, to the beginning of mass production in the 1890s.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] Henry Ford's Model T drove down the price of cars to a more affordable price.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] At the same time, Charles Kettering invented an electric starter, allowing the engine to be started without the need for a mechanical hand crank.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] The abundance of fuel propelled gas automobiles to be highly capable and affordable.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] The demand of gasoline rose from 3 billion barrels in 1919 to around 15 billion in 1929.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] An internal combustion engine (ICE) is powered by the expansion of gas which is created by the combustion of hydrocarbon gases fuels.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] To elaborate, an internal combustion used the heat of a combustion created by the injected hydrocarbon fuel to create mechanical motion.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] At the time of the early 1900s, wood alcohol was a popular fuel for French and German automobiles, but as governments imposed large taxes on the production, the price of wood alcohol rose above that of gasoline.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] Gasoline engines became popular as a result of this, as ICE engines were commonly known as gasoline engines.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] Although gasoline engines became popular, they were not particularly desirable due to the dangers of fuel leaks that may cause explosions.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] Therefore, many inventors attempted to create a kerosene burning engine as a result.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] This was not a successful venture applying it for automotive usage.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] There are many different types of fuels for ICE engines.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] These include diesel, gasoline, and ethanol.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] The steam engine was invented in the late 1700s, and the primary method of powering engines and soon, locomotives.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] One of the most popular steam automobiles was the “Stanley Steamer,” offering low pollution, power, and speed.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] The downside of these steam automobiles is the unreliability, complexity, and the frequent accidents that occurred with them.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] The startup time for a steam car may take up to 45 minutes, defeating the purpose of faster transportation.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] By the time the steam automobile was improved, the complexity of manufacturing relative to the gas automobiles made steam automobiles unprofitable.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] A steam engine is a device which transforms heat into mechanical motion.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] This is provided with the usage of boilers, which create steam by boiling water.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] In the early 1900s, Abner Doble introduced a steam-powered car in the United States which had capabilities that could potentially overpower Ford's Model T in efficiency.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] Steam has been known to have very efficient fuel economy with a high power source.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] That is why half the world was powered by steam for almost the entirety of the 19th century and almost half the 20th century.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] The main drawback of the steam engine in automobiles was that operators were required to have full knowledge of boilers and steam engines before operating, as it was detrimental to the engine itself if the operator neglected it.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] Electric vehicles seemed to be the most viable option, similar to the steam automobiles.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] They were first invented in the early 1800s, and became a viable option of transportation around 1890, when William Morrison created the first electric car that traveled 14 miles per hour.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] The electric cars offered low pollution and a soundless ride, unlike their gasoline counterparts.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] The greatest downside of electric cars was the range.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] The typical electric car could reach around 20 miles before requiring a recharge.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] Manufacturers could not increase the number of batteries, due to the bulkiness of the batteries at the time.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] Without an incentive to purchase the electric automobiles, gas automobiles were the most viable option at the time.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] Electric cars use batteries to store electricity which is used to power electric motors.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] The battery delivers the power to the motor, which is either Alternating Current (AC) or Direct Current (DC).
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] The difference between AC and DC motors is the sort of system that is required to run it in an electric vehicle.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] An AC motor is generally cheaper but the components required to run it in an electric vehicle such as the controller and inverter makes it more expensive than the DC motor.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] A unique feature of electric vehicles compared to its gasoline counterparts, the electric vehicle is more simple than the gasoline vehicle.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] The electric vehicle bypasses the gasoline car components such as the crankshaft which allows it to generate power much faster than gasoline.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] Because of the faster transfer of power, the electric vehicle is able to accelerate faster than gasoline cars.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] In the 1970s, the electric vehicle made its reappearance because of the 1973 OPEC Oil Embargo.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] Previously, the abundant gasoline had become the prime source of fuel for vehicles.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] But after the shortage, manufacturers began looking towards electric vehicles again.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] Despite the improved technology from the 1800s, the electric vehicles faced similar technological flaws such as limited mileage and speed.
[src:moving-parts/automobile-engine] They could only travel up to 45 miles per hour and had a range of approximately 40 miles.
[src:moving-parts/axle] An **axle** or **axletree** is a central shaft for a rotating wheel or gear.
[src:moving-parts/axle] On wheeled vehicles, the axle may be fixed to the wheels, rotating with them, or fixed to the vehicle, with the wheels rotating around the axle.
[src:moving-parts/axle] In the former case, bearings or bushings are provided at the mounting points where the axle is supported.
[src:moving-parts/axle] In the latter case, a bearing or bushing sits inside a central hole in the wheel to allow the wheel or gear to rotate around the axle.
[src:moving-parts/axle] Sometimes, especially on bicycles, the latter type of axle is referred to as a *spindle*.
[src:moving-parts/axle] On cars and trucks, several senses of the word *axle* occur in casual usage, referring to the shaft itself, its housing, or simply any transverse pair of wheels.
[src:moving-parts/axle] Strictly speaking, a shaft that rotates with the wheel, being either bolted or splined in fixed relation to it, is called an *axle* or *axle shaft*.
[src:moving-parts/axle] However, in looser usage, an entire assembly including the surrounding axle housing (typically a casting) is also called an *axle*.
[src:moving-parts/axle] An even broader (somewhat figurative) sense of the word refers to every pair of parallel wheels on opposite sides of a vehicle, regardless of their mechanical connection to each other and to the vehicle frame or body.
[src:moving-parts/axle] Thus, transverse pairs of wheels in an independent suspension may be called an *axle* in some contexts.
[src:moving-parts/axle] This very loose definition of "axle" is often used in assessing toll roads or vehicle taxes, and is taken as a rough proxy for the overall weight-bearing capacity of a vehicle, and its potential for causing wear or damage to roadway surfaces.
[src:moving-parts/axle] Axles are an integral component of most practical wheeled vehicles.
[src:moving-parts/axle] The solid axles (housings) in this system must also bear the weight of the vehicle plus any cargo.
[src:moving-parts/axle] A non-driving axle, such as the front beam axle in heavy-duty trucks and some two-wheel drive light trucks and vans, will have no shaft, and serves only as a suspension and steering component.
[src:moving-parts/axle] Conversely, many front-wheel drive cars have a one-piece rear beam axle.
[src:moving-parts/axle] In other types of suspension systems, the axles serve only to transmit driving torque to the wheels: the position and angle of the wheel hubs is made independent from the axles by the function of the suspension system.
[src:moving-parts/axle] This is typical of the independent suspensions found on most newer cars, and even SUVs, and on the front of many light trucks.
[src:moving-parts/axle] An exception to this rule is the independent (rear) swing axle suspension, wherein the half-axles are also load-bearing suspension arms.
[src:moving-parts/axle] Independent drive-trains still need differentials (or diffs), but without fixed axle-housing tubes attached.
[src:moving-parts/axle] The diff may be attached to the vehicle frame or body, and/or be integrated with the transmission (or gearbox) in a combined transaxle unit.
[src:moving-parts/axle] The axle (half-)shafts then transmit driving torque to the wheels, usually via constant-velocity joints.
[src:moving-parts/axle] Like a full floating axle system, the drive shafts in a front-wheel-drive independent suspension system do not support any vehicle weight.
[src:moving-parts/axle] A straight axle is a single rigid shaft connecting a wheel on the left side of the vehicle to a wheel on the right side.
[src:moving-parts/axle] The axis of rotation fixed by the axle is common to both wheels.
[src:moving-parts/axle] Such a design can keep the wheel positions steady under heavy stress, and can therefore support heavy loads.
[src:moving-parts/axle] Straight axles are used on trains (that is, locomotives and railway wagons), for the rear axles of commercial trucks, and on heavy-duty off-road vehicles.
[src:moving-parts/axle] The axle can optionally be protected and further reinforced by enclosing the length of the axle in a housing.
[src:moving-parts/axle] In split-axle designs, the wheel on each side is attached to a separate shaft.
[src:moving-parts/axle] Modern passenger cars have split-drive axles.
[src:moving-parts/axle] In some designs, this allows independent suspension of the left and right wheels, and therefore a smoother ride.
[src:moving-parts/axle] Even when the suspension is not independent, split axles permit the use of a differential, allowing the left and right drive wheels to be driven at different speeds as the automobile turns, improving traction and extending tire life.
[src:moving-parts/axle] A tandem axle is a group of two or more axles situated close together.
[src:moving-parts/axle] Truck designs use such a configuration to provide a greater weight capacity than a single axle.
[src:moving-parts/axle] Semi-trailers usually have a tandem axle at the rear.
[src:moving-parts/axle] Axles are typically made from SAE grade 41xx steel or SAE grade 10xx steel.
[src:moving-parts/axle] SAE grade 41xx steel is commonly known as "chrome-molybdenum steel" (or "chrome-moly") while SAE grade 10xx steel is known as "carbon steel".
[src:moving-parts/axle] The primary differences between the two are that chrome-moly steel is significantly more resistant to bending or breaking, and is very difficult to weld with tools normally found outside a professional welding shop.
[src:moving-parts/axle] An axle that is driven by the engine or prime mover is called a *drive axle*.
[src:moving-parts/axle] Modern front-wheel drive cars typically combine the transmission (gearbox and differential) and front axle into a single unit called a *transaxle*.
[src:moving-parts/axle] The drive axle is a split axle with a differential and universal joints between the two half axles.
[src:moving-parts/axle] Each half axle connects to the wheel by use of a constant velocity (CV) joint which allows the wheel assembly to move freely vertically as well as to pivot when making turns.
[src:moving-parts/axle] In rear-wheel drive cars and trucks, the engine turns a driveshaft (also called a *propeller shaft* or *tailshaft*) which transmits the rotational force to a drive axle at the rear of the vehicle.
[src:moving-parts/axle] The drive axle may be a live axle, but modern rear-wheel drive automobiles generally use a split axle with a differential.
[src:moving-parts/axle] In this case, one half-axle or half-shaft connects the differential with the left rear wheel, a second half-shaft does the same with the right rear wheel; thus the two half-axles and the differential constitute the rear axle.
[src:moving-parts/axle] The front drive axle is providing the force to drive the truck.
[src:moving-parts/axle] In fact, only one wheel of that axle is actually moving the truck and trailer down the road.
[src:moving-parts/axle] Some simple vehicle designs, such as leisure go-karts, may have a single driven wheel where the drive axle is a split axle with only one of the two shafts driven by the engine, or else have both wheels connected to one shaft without a differential (kart racing).
[src:moving-parts/axle] However, other go-karts have two rear drive wheels too.
[src:moving-parts/axle] Some dump trucks and trailers may be configured with a lift axle (also known as an *airlift axle* or *drop axle*), which may be mechanically raised or lowered.
[src:moving-parts/axle] The axle is lowered to increase the weight capacity, or to distribute the weight of the cargo over more wheels, for example, to cross a weight-restricted bridge.
[src:moving-parts/axle] When not needed, the axle is lifted off the ground to save wear on the tires and axle, and to increase traction in the remaining wheels, and to decrease fuel consumption.
[src:moving-parts/axle] Lifting an axle also alleviates lateral scrubbing of the additional axle in very tight turns, allowing the vehicle to turn more readily.
[src:moving-parts/axle] In some situations, the removal of pressure from the additional axle is necessary for the vehicle to complete a turn at all.
[src:moving-parts/axle] Several manufacturers offer computer-controlled airlifts so that the dead axles are automatically lowered when the main axle reaches its weight limit.
[src:moving-parts/axle] The dead axles can still be lifted by the press of a button if needed, for better maneuverability.
[src:moving-parts/axle] Lift axles were in use in the early 1940s.
[src:moving-parts/axle] Initially, the axle was lifted by a mechanical device.
[src:moving-parts/axle] Soon hydraulics replaced the mechanical lift system.
[src:moving-parts/axle] One of the early manufacturers was Zetterbergs, located in Östervåla, Sweden.
[src:moving-parts/axle] The liftable tandem drive axle was invented in 1957 by the Finnish truck manufacturer Vanajan Autotehdas, a company sharing history with Sisu Auto.
[src:moving-parts/axle] A full-floating axle carries the vehicle's weight on the axle casing, not the half-shafts; they serve only to transmit torque from the differential to the wheels.
[src:moving-parts/axle] They "float" inside an assembly that carries the vehicle's weight.
[src:moving-parts/axle] Thus the only stress it must endure is torque (not lateral bending force).
[src:moving-parts/axle] Full-floating axle shafts are retained by a flange bolted to the hub, while the hub and bearings are retained on the spindle by a large nut.
[src:moving-parts/axle] In contrast, a semi-floating design carries the weight of the vehicle on the axle shaft itself; there is a single bearing at the end of the axle housing that carries the load from the axle and that the axle rotates through.
[src:moving-parts/axle] To be "semi-floating" the axle shafts must be able to "float" in the housing, bearings and seals, and not subject to axial "thrust" and/or bearing preload.
[src:moving-parts/axle] A true semi-floating axle assembly places no side loads on the axle housing tubes or axle shafts.
[src:moving-parts/axle] Axles that are pressed into ball or tapered roller bearings, which are in turn retained in the axle housings with flanges, bolts, and nuts do not "float" and place axial loads on the bearings, housings, and only a short section of the shaft itself, that also carries all radial loads.
[src:moving-parts/axle] The full-floating design is typically used in most ¾- and 1-ton light trucks, medium-duty trucks, and heavy-duty trucks.
[src:moving-parts/axle] The overall assembly can carry more weight than a semi-floating or non-floating axle assembly because the hubs have two bearings riding on a fixed spindle.
[src:moving-parts/axle] A full-floating axle can be identified by a protruding hub to which the axle shaft flange is bolted.
[src:moving-parts/axle] The semi-floating axle setup is commonly used on half-ton and lighter 4×4 trucks in the rear.
[src:moving-parts/axle] This setup allows the axle shaft to be the means of propulsion, and also support the weight of the vehicle.
[src:moving-parts/axle] The main difference between the full- and semi-floating axle setups is the number of bearings.
[src:moving-parts/axle] The semi-floating axle features only one bearing, while the full-floating assembly has bearings on both the inside and outside of the wheel hub.
[src:moving-parts/axle] To remove the semi-floating axle, the wheel must be removed first; if such an axle breaks, the wheel is most likely to come off the vehicle.
[src:moving-parts/axle] The semi-floating design is found under most ½-ton and lighter trucks, as well as in SUVs and rear-wheel-drive passenger cars, usually being smaller or less expensive models.
[src:moving-parts/axle] A benefit of a full-floating axle is that even if an axle shaft (used to transmit torque or power) breaks, the wheel will not come off, preventing serious accidents.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] Machines include both fixed and **moving parts**.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] The moving parts have controlled and constrained motions.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] The term excludes fluids that pass through the machine, such as fuel, coolant or hydraulic fluid, as well as mechanical parts (such as locks, switches, nuts, bolts, and screw caps for bottles) which are moved only to reconfigure the machine.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] A system with no moving parts is described as "solid state".
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] The amount of moving parts in a machine is a factor in its mechanical efficiency.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] The greater the number of moving parts, the greater the amount of energy lost to heat by friction between those parts.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] For example, in a modern automobile engine, roughly 7% of the total power obtained from burning the engine's fuel is lost to friction between the engine's moving parts.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] Conversely, the fewer the number of moving parts, the greater the efficiency.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] Machines with no moving parts at all can be very efficient.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] An electrical transformer, for example, has no moving parts, and its mechanical efficiency is generally above the 90% mark.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] Two means are used for overcoming the efficiency losses caused by friction between moving parts.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] Second, the moving parts of a machine are designed so that they have a small amount of contact with one another.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] The latter, in its turn, comprises two approaches.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] A machine can be reduced in size, thereby quite simply reducing the areas of the moving parts that rub against one another; and the designs of the individual components can be modified, changing their shapes and structures to reduce or avoid contact with one another.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] Lubrication also reduces wear, as does the use of suitable materials.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] As moving parts wear out, this can affect the precision of the machine.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] Designers thus have to design moving parts with this factor in mind, ensuring that if precision over the lifetime of the machine is paramount, that wear is accounted for and, if possible, minimized.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] (A simple example of this is the design of a simple single-wheel wheelbarrow.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] The scientific and engineering discipline that deals with the lubrication, friction, and wear of moving parts is tribology, an interdisciplinary field that encompasses materials science, mechanical engineering, chemistry, and mechanics.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] As mentioned, wear is a concern for moving parts in a machine.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] Other concerns that lead to failure include corrosion, erosion, thermal stress and heat generation, vibration, fatigue loading, and cavitation.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] Fatigue is related to large inertial forces, and is affected by the type of motion that a moving part has.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] A moving part that has a uniform rotation motion is subject to less fatigue than a moving part that oscillates back and forth.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] Vibration leads to failure when the *forcing frequency* of the machine's operation hits a resonant frequency of one or more moving parts, such as rotating shafts.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] Designers avoid these problems by calculating the natural frequencies of the parts at design time, and altering the parts to limit or eliminate such resonance.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] Yet further factors that can lead to failure of moving parts include failures in the cooling and lubrication systems of a machine.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] One final, particular, factor related to failure of moving parts is kinetic energy.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] The sudden release of the kinetic energy of the moving parts of a machine causes overstress failures if a moving part is impeded in its motion by a foreign object.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] For example, consider a stone caught on the blades of a fan or propeller, or even the proverbial "spanner/monkey wrench in the works".
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] The kinetic energy of a machine is the sum of the kinetic energies of its individual moving parts.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] A machine with moving parts can, mathematically, be treated as a connected system of bodies, whose kinetic energies are simply summed.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] The individual kinetic energies are determined from the kinetic energies of the moving parts' translations and rotations about their axes.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] This ideal ring is known as the *equivalent flywheel*, whose radius is the *radius of gyration*.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] The rotational kinetic energy of the whole system of moving parts is ${\frac {1}{2}}I\omega ^{2}$ , where $\omega$ is the angular velocity of the moving parts about the same axis as the moment of inertia.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] The *kinetic energy of translation* of the moving parts is ${\frac {1}{2}}mv^{2}$ , where m is the total mass and v is the magnitude of the velocity.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] This gives the formula for the *total kinetic energy of the moving parts of a machine* as ${\frac {1}{2}}I\omega ^{2}+{\frac {1}{2}}mv^{2}$ .
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] These conventions are enshrined in several standards from the American National Standards Institute and the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, including ASME Y14.2M published in 1979.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] In recent decades, the use of animation has become more practical and widespread in technical and engineering diagrams for the illustration of the motions of moving parts.
[src:moving-parts/moving-parts] Animation represents moving parts more clearly and enables them and their motions to be more readily visualized.
